Show HN: A tiny WASM compiler and runtime for demonstration purposes
text:
Hello, I'm building a WebAssembly compiler and documenting the process in the meantime. This aims to be a tool for demonstration and education purpose. It doesn't aim to do fancy stuff nor to replace existing ones. I'm building this to learn and to improve and hopefully it can be useful for others as well :)

From last time I've presented the idea, I've implemented more basic features on Luna and I've built a custom and tiny runtime for Luna! (documenting it of course).

Any feedback is really appreciated :)

Repo: https://github.com/thomscoder/luna

title: The Brave Little Toaster (1987)
Show HN: Complete the challenge and get interviewed
text:
Hello HN,

It's been a while since I've been active. A lot has been going on! It's been good, bad, amazing and awful over the last couple of years, from COVID and loss, to a new job and so on...

I've finally started my dream project and would love to share it with you all. It's called The Job Challenge (thejobchallenge.com).

The idea is pretty simple. If you complete the challenge, you get interviewed. Completing the challenge proves you're capable. The remaining steps are up to the employers. I'm hoping to be able to cut out a lot of the technical interview process as well as all those spammy emails from recruiters.

I thought this project up years ago when I first started looking for a job as a software engineer. I had already been programming for several years before then but found the job-hunting process to be incredibly tedious and painful with arbitrary requirements that made no sense. Coming from a self-taught hobby background with no college/uni, I felt that (and discovered later) my resumes were being filtered out long before getting into the hands of an interviewing engineer.

I'm looking to partner with employers that understand the challenges engineers face in this process and who want to save time and money on finding talent.

Also, if you're an engineer that's happy where you're at but resonates with the mission, I'd love to talk. There's quite a bit of work to do.

Much love, HN <3

thejobchallenge.com

Ask HN: Why is my new residential fiber gateway box so heavy and so hot?
text:
My ISP recently upgraded my home to fiber (from DSL copper) and provided for the connection a Nokia BGW320 Wireless Integrated ONT Residential Gateway. They took away the old DSL gateway box I had previously had for ten years.

I soon noticed that the new unit, while physically a tiny bit smaller than the prior unit, weighed 2 kg (4.5 lbs), which seems really heavy to me. And there is a sticker on it with the warning "Hot metal surfaces".

What is going on here? Does it have something to do with the power of the wifi service (which I don't use). I can't help but think of some kind of electromagnet...
